Make a plot of the outcome (CompressiveStrength) versus the index of the samples. Color by each of the variables in the data set (you may find the cut2() function in the Hmisc package useful for turning continuous covariates into factors). What do you notice in these plots?

Possible answers:

  1. There is a non-random pattern in the plot of the outcome versus index that does not appear to be perfectly explained by any predictor suggesting a variable may be missing. Yes?

  2. There is a non-random pattern in the plot of the outcome versus index.

  3. There is a non-random pattern in the plot of the outcome versus index that is perfectly explained by the Age variable.

  4. There is a non-random pattern in the plot of the outcome versus index that is perfectly explained by the FlyAsh variable.

Compressive Strength versus Age

library(splines)
bsBasis = bs(training$Age, df = 3)
plot(training$Age, training$CompressiveStrength)
points(training$Age, 
      predict(lm(CompressiveStrength ~ bsBasis, data = training), 
              newdata = training), 
      col = "red")

plot(training$Age, training$CompressiveStrength)
# I(Age*Age) + Age
points(training$Age, 
      predict(lm(CompressiveStrength ~ I(atan(Age/25)) + I(Age*Age), data = training), 
              newdata = training), 
      col = "red")

summary(lm(CompressiveStrength ~ I(atan(Age/25)) + I(Age*Age) + Cement + Water + BlastFurnaceSlag + Superplasticizer, data = training))
